Integration of Resequencing and RNA-seq Data(Focus on MCM3AP)

Shakiba Hamedi

2026-02-14

Introduction

Overview

The identification of disease-associated genes benefits from integrating complementary layers of molecular evidence. While resequencing enables the detection of potentially functional DNA variants, RNA-seq provides quantitative insight into transcriptional alterations between cases and controls.

Combining these datasets strengthens candidate gene prioritization by linking structural genomic variation with transcriptional dysregulation.

In this study, we performed a structured multi-omics integration analysis focusing on chromosome 21, with particular attention to the gene ENSG00000160294 (MCM3AP). MCM3AP encodes a protein associated with the minichromosome maintenance complex and is implicated in DNA replication initiation and chromatin-associated processes.

Variants identified through the nf-core/sarek pipeline were annotated and prioritized based on predicted functional impact and pathogenicity metrics. In parallel, differential gene expression analysis was conducted using DESeq2 to identify significantly dysregulated genes.

By intersecting genes harboring prioritized variants with significantly differentially expressed genes, we aimed to refine candidate gene selection and highlight biologically plausible contributors to the simulated disease phenotype. This reproducible workflow demonstrates how variant-level and expression-level evidence can be systematically integrated to enhance gene prioritization.

Test Information

All analyses were performed on a Google Cloud Platform Virtual Machine.

Pipelines: nf-core/sarek (v3.4.4), (variant calling + SnpEff annotation) and nf-core/rnaseq (v3.16.1)

Tools:pseudo_aligner: salmon, aligner bwa-mem2, haplotypecaller, snpeff

Reference genome: GRCh38chr21.

Differential expression: DESeq2 for casecontrol comparison and identification of significantly deregulated genes.

Integration and downstream analysis: R (tidyverse, VariantAnnotation, tximport, clusterProfiler) for variant filtering, DEG integration, and visualization.

Analysis

Workflow and Methodology

The analytical workflow consisted of four major steps:

RNA-seq quantification and differential expression analysis using the nf-core/rnaseq pipeline and DESeq2.

Variant calling and functional annotation using the nf-core/sarek pipeline with SnpEff/VEP annotation.

Data integration, intersecting differentially expressed genes (DEGs) with genes harboring annotated variants.

Variant prioritization, applying filtering criteria and pathogenicity predictors to refine candidate genes.

This structured pipeline enables systematic integration of genomic and transcriptomic evidence within a reproducible computational framework.

Differential gene expression analysis

Transcript-level quantifications generated by the nf-core/rnaseq pipeline (Salmon) were imported into R using the tximport package and summarized at the gene level based on the provided tx2gene annotation.

A DESeq2 object was constructed from the count matrix and corresponding sample metadata. Differential expression analysis was performed using the model:

expression ~ condition

DESeq2 estimated size factors for normalization and gene-wise dispersion parameters, followed by Wald tests to assess differential expression between cases and controls. Log2 fold changes and adjusted p-values (BenjaminiHochberg correction) were computed for each gene.

This analysis generated a statistically robust set of differentially expressed genes (DEGs), providing the foundation for downstream functional enrichment and integrative multi-omics prioritization.

Set conditions

A DESeqDataSet object was created from the imported count matrix and associated sample information, ensuring proper alignment between expression data and experimental design.

To improve statistical power and reduce noise, genes with very low overall counts (sum < 10 across all samples) were filtered out prior to differential testing.

The reference level for the condition factor was set to control to ensure biologically interpretable log2 fold changes.

Differential expression analysis was subsequently performed using DESeq2 with default statistical parameters.

sample condition
control_rep1 control
control_rep2 control
control_rep3 control
treatment_rep1 case
treatment_rep2 case
treatment_rep3 case

Prefiltering

To improve statistical power and reduce noise from minimally expressed genes, a prefiltering step was applied prior to differential testing. Genes with very low overall counts (sum < 10 across all samples) were excluded from downstream analysis.

This filtering strategy minimizes the influence of genes with insufficient read support, thereby improving dispersion estimation and the reliability of statistical inference in DESeq2.

The reference level of the condition factor was set to control, ensuring that estimated log2 fold changes reflect expression differences relative to the biologically appropriate baseline.

Differential expression analysis was subsequently performed using DESeq2 with default parameters.

keep <- rowSums(counts(dds)) >= 10
dds <- dds[keep,]
dds$condition <- relevel(dds$condition, ref = "control")
dds <- DESeq(dds)

A total of 229 genes were retained for differential expression analysis. Among these, 48 genes met the significance threshold after multiple-testing correction. Of the significant genes, 36(16%) were upregulated and 12(5.2%) were downregulated in cases relative to controls.

No outlier samples were detected, and no genes were excluded due to low counts after the applied prefiltering step.

Overall, approximately 21% of the analyzed genes showed statistically significant differential expression, with a predominance of upregulation, indicating a condition-associated transcriptional shif

Data visualization

MA plot

Plot showing the log2 fold change over the mean of normalized counts for analysed samples

The MA plot shows the mean of the normalized counts versus the log2 foldchanges for all genes tested. The genes that are significantly DE are colored (blue) to be easily identified.

Dispersion plot

Dispersion plot from DESeq2 analysis

This plot shows the relationship between the mean of normalized counts and gene-wise dispersion estimates. Each black dot represents the estimated dispersion for an individual gene. The red line indicates the fitted dispersion trend across genes, while the blue points show the final shrunk dispersion estimates used for differential expression testing. As expected, dispersion decreases with increasing mean expression, reflecting lower variability in highly expressed genes.

Clustring analysis and Visualization

The heatmap represents hierarchical clustering of selected genes based on normalized expression values across control and case samples.

A clear separation between the two experimental groups is observed. Control replicates cluster together, while case (treatment) replicates form a distinct cluster. This indicates strong consistency within groups and substantial transcriptional differences between conditions.

Key observations:

Biological replicates show high similarity within each group, confirming good experimental reproducibility.

Case samples display a coordinated expression pattern distinct from controls.

Several genes show consistent upregulation in cases (red signal) and downregulation in controls (blue signal), suggesting a disease-associated transcriptional signature.

Importantly, the gene of interest (ENSG00000160294 MCM3AP) follows the same clustering trend, supporting its differential expression and reinforcing its potential involvement in the simulated disease phenotype.

Plot Principal Component Aanalysis

Useful for visualizing the overall effect of experimental covariates and batch effects.

The PCA plot shows a clear separation between control and case samples along PC1, which explains 79% of the total variance. This indicates that the primary source of variation in the dataset corresponds to the experimental condition.

Control samples cluster tightly on one side of the plot, while case samples form a distinct cluster on the opposite side, demonstrating strong transcriptional differences between groups.

The limited dispersion within groups and the absence of overlap suggest high reproducibility and minimal batch effects.

Overall, the PCA analysis confirms that the disease condition has a major impact on global gene expression patterns.

RNAseq and resequencing data integration

Variant calling and annotation

The VCF file generated by the nf-core/sarek pipeline (v3.4.4) contained pre-computed functional annotations from SnpEff. Variant-level information was extracted and structured into an analysis-ready table including genomic coordinates, REF/ALT alleles, sample genotypes, and functional predictions.

Using rowRanges(vcf), genomic positions and allele information were formatted. Genotype data were incorporated from geno(vcf)$GT, enabling comparison between case and control samples.

The INFO/ANN field was parsed to retrieve the most severe predicted annotation per variant, including affected gene, transcript ID, amino acid change, functional consequence, and impact classification (HIGH, MODERATE, LOW, MODIFIER).

This processing step transformed raw VCF output into a structured dataset suitable for downstream filtering and integrative analysis.

vcf <- readVcf(params$vcf)
variants <- rowRanges(vcf)
variants$`REF` <- as.character(variants$`REF`)
variants$ALT <- sapply(variants$ALT, function(x) as.character(x)[1])
variants <- as_tibble(variants)
variants$variantName = names(rowRanges(vcf))
variants = cbind(variants, as_tibble(geno(vcf)$GT))
names(variants)[names(variants) == "patient_01_sample_01"] <- "case_case1"
names(variants)[names(variants) == "patient_02_sample_02"] <- "control_control1"
variants$gene <- unlist(lapply(info(vcf)$ANN, get_most_severe_gene))
variants$ens <- unlist(lapply(info(vcf)$ANN, get_most_severe_ens))
variants$transcript <- unlist(lapply(info(vcf)$ANN, get_most_severe_tr))
variants$aa_change <- unlist(lapply(info(vcf)$ANN, get_most_severe_aa_change))
variants$consequence <- unlist(lapply(info(vcf)$ANN, get_most_severe_consequence))
variants$impact <- unlist(lapply(info(vcf)$ANN, get_most_severe_impact))

Functional annotation of the 2,168 detected variants revealed that the majority correspond to synonymous variants (n = 1433), followed by missense variants (n = 614) and a smaller proportion of intronic variants (n = 37).

Higher-impact categories were relatively rare, including frameshift variants (n = 8), splice-region variants (n = 7), and single occurrences of start-loss and stop-gained mutations.

This distribution is consistent with expectations for coding-region analyses, where most variants are predicted to have neutral or moderate effects at the protein level, while potentially disruptive mutations occur less frequently.

A list of 2168 variants

Variant Filtering

Filtering Criteria

To prioritize potentially functionally relevant variants, a stepwise filtering strategy was applied.

The following criteria were used:

Missense variants only, to focus on protein-altering substitutions.

Variants absent in control samples (genotype 0/0), retaining variants observed exclusively in cases.

Predicted impact classified as MODERATE or HIGH according to SnpEff annotation.

Variants located in significantly differentially expressed genes, linking structural variation with transcriptional dysregulation.

After applying these filters, 146 variants remained, distributed across 23 genes.

This filtering approach substantially reduced the initial variant set and enriched for candidates with potential functional and condition-specific relevance.

filteredVars <- variants %>%
  filter(
    control_control1 %in% c("0/0", "0|0") &               
      impact %in% c("MODERATE", "HIGH") &
      ens %in% significant_de_genes &                   
      consequence == "missense_variant"                    
  )

Additional annotations and Pathogenicity Predictions of filtered variants

The Ensembl Variant Effect PredictorVEP web tool is used for additional annotations and prediction the effect of filtered variants on gene transcripts and protein sequences.

The following annotations were used to prioritize potentially pathogenic variants on the next step:

SIFT a protein-level prediction of deleteriousness for missense variants (tolerated vs deleterious) (v 6.2.1)

PolyPhen a protein-level predictor indicating the possible impact of amino acid substitutions on protein structure and function (v 2.2.3)

am_class pathogenicity prediction from AlphaMissense (likely_pathogenic, ambiguous, likely_benign)

am_pathogenicity AlphaMissense pathogenecity score providing the likelihood of pathogenicity

LOEUF metric reflecting tolerance to loss-of-function variants

gnomAD - database which contains information about the frequency of a variant in the population (v 4.1)

*Some external annotations (e.g., gnomAD AF) were missing for the top variant and were reported as NA/not found as required.

ClinVar - public archive of reports of the relationships among human variations and phenotypes (reliased on February, 2025)

Prioritized variants

To prioritize variants that are both functionally impactful at the protein level and predicted to be pathogenic we have chosen only missense variants with HIGH or MODERATE impact (this step was done before at the filtering step) and likely pathogenic according AlphaMissense prediction.

All 163 observations fall into list of just 14 genes (e.g., CFAP298, CLIC6, RUNX1, DYRK1A, DSCAM, TRPM2, ITGB2, COL6A1/COL6A2, COL18A1, etc).

After applying the most stringent, high-confidence prioritization filters (AlphaMissense likely_pathogenic/ambiguous + deleterious SIFT + possibly/probably damaging PolyPhen + ClinVar pathogenic), we found that all remaining prioritized variants mapped to a single gene: MCM3AP (ENSG00000160294). In our dataset, MCM3AP is not only differentially expressed between cases and controls (with markedly higher normalized counts in cases), but it is also the only gene that retains variants meeting all high-confidence pathogenicity criteria simultaneously, making it the strongest candidate to explain the simulated disease signal and a prime target for downstream functional follow-up.

At the variant level, the retained MCM3AP missense signal is supported by convergent pathogenicity evidence: the candidate variant(s) at 21:46267138 are predicted deleterious by SIFT (0) and probably damaging by PolyPhen (1), annotated as pathogenic in ClinVar, and classified as likely_pathogenic by AlphaMissense with an am_pathogenicity score of 0.9027. Additionally, the gnomAD allele frequency is missing (-) in our annotation table, suggesting the variant is not represented (or not captured) in the referenced population frequency field. The LOEUF score for MCM3AP (~0.769) indicates the gene is moderately tolerant to loss-of-function, meaning LoF variation can exist in the population, but this does not exclude a meaningful role for damaging missense variationespecially when combined with clear casecontrol expression separation.

Note: Under less strict prioritization, additional genes still carried likely_pathogenic missense variants (e.g., CFAP298, CLIC6, RUNX1, DYRK1A, DSCAM, TRPM2, ITGB2, COL6A1/COL6A2, COL18A1, etc.). These should remain in the interpretation as secondary candidates (potential modifiers, pathway-level contributors, or context-dependent effects), but MCM3AP uniquely persists as the single gene supported by the strictest combined evidence framework in this report.

Conclusion

This integrated multi-omics analysis combined whole-exome resequencing and RNA-seq data to systematically prioritise candidate variants potentially involved in the simulated disease phenotype.

A total of 2168 variants were initially identified from the nf-core/sarek pipeline. After applying a stringent filtering strategy;restricting to missense variants with MODERATE or HIGH impact, absent in controls, and occurring in significantly differentially expressed genes,146 high-confidence variants across 23 genes were retained.

RNA-seq analysis identified 48 significantly differentially expressed genes (36 upregulated, 12 downregulated) between cases and controls. The intersection of variant-level and expression-level evidence resulted in 14 shared genes, representing the strongest biologically supported candidates.

Under the most stringent pathogenicity framework (AlphaMissense likely_pathogenic, deleterious SIFT, probably damaging PolyPhen, and ClinVar pathogenic annotations), MCM3AP emerged as the single gene retaining convergent high-confidence evidence. Importantly, MCM3AP is also significantly differentially expressed, strengthening its candidacy as a potential driver of the simulated disease signal.

Overall, this report demonstrates a transparent and reproducible prioritisation strategy integrating structural genetic variation and transcriptomic dysregulation, successfully narrowing thousands of variants to a biologically coherent, high-confidence candidate gene for downstream functional validation.

Explicit Answers to Exam Questions

1. How many variants were identified in total?

A total of 2168 were identified from the nf-core/sarek VCF output before applying any filtering criteria.

2. How many variants were prioritised? What were the inclusion criteria?

After applying a stringent filtering strategy with combining DEA results , 146 were prioritised in 23 genes.

The inclusion criteria were:

  • Genotype in control sample = 0/0

  • Variant impact classified as HIGH or MODERATE (SnpEff annotation)

  • Consequence type: missense_variant

  • Gene significantly differentially expressed (adjusted p-value < 0.05)

  • External pathogenicity evidence from:

    • AlphaMissense (score threshold)
    • SIFT (deleterious)
    • PolyPhen (probably damaging)
    • gnomAD allele frequency (v 4.1)
    • ClinVar (reliased on February, 2025)

3. Which/How many genes harbour prioritised pathogenic variants?

A total of 146 (146 unique variants/163 transcript-level annotations (VEP multi-transcript))were found to harbour prioritised pathogenic variants is in 14 genes (from DEA)

These genes represent strong candidates potentially contributing to the simulated disease phenotype due to predicted functional impact at the protein level.
